Fantastic question â€” this gets to the core difference between having own properties vs. being mutable.
You're asking:
â€œIf the string object (new String("abc")) has 0, 1, 2 as own properties, then why canâ€™t I mutate them like strObj[1] = 'x'?â€
âš ï¸ The key is:
Even though index properties (like "0", "1", etc.) exist as own properties on new String() objects, they are:
ğŸ‘‰ Non-writable
Meaning you cannot change them, even though they appear as part of the object.
ğŸ” Proof:
